- Not every function needs a return.
- Use return when you want the function to give back a value that can be stored or reused.
- Skip return when the functionâ€™s job is just to do something (like printing, updating, or triggering an action).


function greet(name) {
  return "Hello, " + name;  // action only
}

// greet("Nasif");   // prints "Hello, Nasif"
console.log(greet("Nasif"));










When would using a switch statement be more appropriate than an if/else statement?

=> When comparing a single value against multiple possible values.
